Possible comorbid conditions such as anxiety and substance use disorders should also be assessed, as they frequently accompany bipolar disorder and may be causing additional impairment (Bauer et al.,
         2005
      ). It is important to consider additional factors that may influence the diagnostic impression, including recent stressors, prescription and recreational drug use, past history of psychotherapy or hospitalizations, and co-occurring medical conditions. Furthermore, the interviewer should be attuned to behavioral cues that may inform the diagnostic picture, including the patient’s affect, rate of speech, quality of eye contact, psychomotor functioning, and personal hygiene. Slowed speech and movement, poor hygiene, and restricted eye contact may be indicators of a possible depressive episode, whereas pressured speech and psychomotor agitation may be signs of hypomania or mania. Examination of prodromal symptoms (e. g., excessive talking or energy, irritable mood, or racing thoughts) is important in the identification of first or recurrent manic episodes (Faedda et al.,
         2019
      ) and can best be assessed via a structured interview (Alvarez-Cadenas et al., 
         2023
      ).

Important information can be gained from additional informants, such as the patient’s significant other, family members, or medical providers including primary care doctors or emergency department staff. Collecting this important information from those closest to the patient can provide valuable insights into a patient’s functioning and help increase diagnostic certainty (Vöhringer & Perlis,
         2016
      ). The assessor should verify whether informed consent is needed by the patient to discuss their functioning with an additional party. As individuals with bipolar disorders may be less likely to report impairment associated with hypomania or mania, observations of outside informants can be particularly helpful in identifying periods of distinct mood changes or unusual, erratic behaviors that may ultimately qualify as hypomanic or manic episodes (Akiskal & Benazzi, 
         2005
      ).

Routine screening for bipolar disorder in the general population is not recommended, especially in the primary care setting, as it may lead to high rates of false positive diagnoses. However, screening using a validated screening tool is recommended when there is suspicion of bipolar disorder (e. g., depressive or manic symptoms present) during a clinical interaction with a patient. The goal of screening tools is to aid in the decision of whether to continue pursuing a bipolar diagnosis. Additional factors to be considered as relevant to pursuing a diagnosis of bipolar disorder include: a first-degree relative with diagnosed bipolar disorder, severe initial onset of depression under the age of 25 or multiple prior episodes of depression, comorbid anxiety/substance use/depression with psychotic features, treatment-resistant depression, and dysregulated sleep patterns (US Department of Veterans Affairs, US Department of Defense,
         2023
      ).
